<subSubSection id="C32AC2BA8E4A98230D85E5A95CE85A23" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E5A95CE85A03" blockId="10.[192,1440,456,475]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,584,603]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<heading id="D0C7265D8E4A98230D85E5A95CE85983" box="[192,1440,456,475]" centered="true" fontSize="10" level="2" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" reason="6">
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230D85E5A9581B5983" authorityName="Corbett" authorityYear="1936" box="[192,339,456,475]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hancocki">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230D85E5A9581B5983" box="[192,339,456,475]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. hancocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
intergrade in many characteristics with 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230E1CE5A95DF65983" authority="Bondar" authorityName="Bondar" box="[857,1214,456,475]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230E1CE5A95D125983" box="[857,1114,456,475]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia tuberculata</emphasis>
Bondar
</taxonomicName>
in South America
</heading>
and with 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C7FE5895B8359A3" authority="(Cockerell)" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[314,715,488,507]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C7FE5895B7F59A3" box="[314,567,488,507]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia berbericola</emphasis>
(Cockerell)
</taxonomicName>
in western North America. There are numerous species described from Eurasia that also belong this species group. African afer complex species tend to have relatively short lingulae compared to some Asian forms, and especially with 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A982309DEE6495C045A63" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[1179,1356,552,571]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A982309DEE6495C045A63" box="[1179,1356,552,571]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the western 
<collectingCountry id="F327D1A18E4A98230C6BE62958AB5A03" box="[302,483,584,603]" name="United States of America" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">United States</collectingCountry>
, in which the lingula can be very long and narrow. Regu and David (1991)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E6095CE85A23" blockId="10.[192,1440,616,635]" box="[192,1440,616,635]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
synonymized 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C2AE609588C5A23" box="[367,452,616,635]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afer">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C2AE609588C5A23" box="[367,452,616,635]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. afer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230F48E6095A505A23" authority="(Peal)" baseAuthorityName="Peal" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[525,792,616,635]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leakii">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230F48E6095B8C5A23" box="[525,708,616,635]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia leakii</emphasis>
(Peal)
</taxonomicName>
based on microspines at the bases of the antennae
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32AC2BA8E4A98220D85E6E95D525CC3" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E6E95CE85B03" blockId="10.[192,1440,648,667]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,840,859]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
(these also occur on 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C8EE6E95BCC5AC3" box="[459,644,648,667]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C8EE6E95BCC5AC3" box="[459,644,648,667]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens from South America) and ridges at the end of the vasiform orifice, but the variability of these characters and thus their reliability as taxonomic have not been assessed. The original illustration of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230E77E6A95AE95A83" baseAuthorityName="Peal" baseAuthorityYear="1903" box="[818,929,712,731]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leakii">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230E77E6A95AE95A83" box="[818,929,712,731]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. leakii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Peal shows an elongated lingula, a characteristic of Asian members of this complex (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230E13E6895C7B5AA3" authority="David and Subramanium" authorityName="David and Subramanium" box="[854,1331,744,763]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moringae">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230E13E6895AA75AA3" box="[854,1007,744,763]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. moringae</emphasis>
David and Subramanium
</taxonomicName>
) and the new World (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230CC1E7695B675B43" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[388,559,776,795]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230CC1E7695B675B43" box="[388,559,776,795]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) rather than the shorter lingulae of Europe and Africa specimens of the afer complex. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230F52E7495B815B63" box="[535,713,808,827]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230F52E7495B815B63" box="[535,713,808,827]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from South America tend to have lingulae of length that is intermediate between those of afer complex specimens from Africa and 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230913E7295C4F5B03" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[1110,1287,840,859]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230913E7295C4F5B03" box="[1110,1287,840,859]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from North
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E7095CE85B23" blockId="10.[192,1440,872,891]" box="[192,1440,872,891]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">America. This also is a variable character and its usefulness as a taxonomic character is unknown.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E7E95A3A5BE3" blockId="10.[192,1440,904,923]" lastBlockId="10.[192,882,936,955]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Populations in the afer complex exhibit extreme morphological variability in the length of dorsal setae and development of rugosities and protuberances.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230DB5E7A95CE85B83" blockId="10.[240,1440,968,987]" box="[240,1440,968,987]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">There are some intriguing characters in some of the species of the afer complex from the</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E7895CE85C63" blockId="10.[192,1440,1000,1019]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,1064,1083]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Macaronesian Islands that are illustrated later. Specimens from one population have a different ommatidial arrangement in the adult compound eyes than those in other other populations, and also have a longer lingula. They also show molecular similarities with specimens from western North</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E0295CE85CE3" blockId="10.[192,1150,1096,1115]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,1192,1211]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
America, which have the same eye configuration (see discussion for 
<figureCitation id="130B8DB48E4A98230953E0295D385C03" box="[1046,1136,1096,1115]" captionStart="Figures 62-80" captionStartId="14.[240,350,1224,1243]" captionText="Figures 62-80: A series of specimens in the afer group from the Canary and Madeira Islands," pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 64</figureCitation>
). seems to be no morphological basis for treating them as separate. It is here considered to be in the afer complex of species. It is apparently African in origin. (Figure reprinted by permission from
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4A98230DB5E0095CE85C23" box="[240,1440,1128,1147]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" startId="10.[240,289,1128,1147]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230DB5E0095CE85C23" blockId="10.[240,1440,1128,1147]" box="[240,1440,1128,1147]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230DB5E009581E5C23" bold="true" box="[240,342,1128,1147]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 16:</emphasis>
Labeled as 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230CB5E0095A755C23" authority="Corbett" authorityName="Corbett" authorityYear="1936" box="[496,829,1128,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hancocki">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230CB5E0095B985C23" box="[496,720,1128,1147]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia hancocki</emphasis>
Corbett
</taxonomicName>
, but may be a synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A982309CAE0095C795C23" box="[1167,1329,1128,1147]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afer">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A982309CAE0095C795C23" box="[1167,1329,1128,1147]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia afer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as there
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E0A95CE85D03" blockId="10.[192,690,1224,1243]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,1352,1371]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Springer Science+Business Media B.V.). numerous long setae and the star-shaped protuberances. It is known from several widely separated localities in Africa, all on the same host species. It is obviously in the afer group, but whether it should have species level status is problematic. The double set of submedial and subdorsal pore-</paragraph>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4A98230DB5E0895CE85CA3" box="[240,1440,1256,1275]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" startId="10.[240,289,1256,1275]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230DB5E0895CE85CA3" blockId="10.[240,1440,1256,1275]" box="[240,1440,1256,1275]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230DB5E08958105CA3" bold="true" box="[240,344,1256,1275]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 17:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C26E0895BBD5CA3" authority="Bink-Moenen" authorityName="Bink-Moenen" box="[355,757,1256,1275]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guieriae">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C26E0895B755CA3" box="[355,573,1256,1275]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia guieriae</emphasis>
Bink-Moenen
</taxonomicName>
is a morphologically striking species because of the
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E1095CE85DC3" blockId="10.[192,1440,1384,1403]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,1416,1435]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
porette pairs could be host-induced variation. A similar morphological response can be seen in the specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C36E1E95B605DC3" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[371,552,1416,1435]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C36E1E95B605DC3" box="[371,552,1416,1435]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from oak in 
<figureCitation id="130B8DB48E4A98230F9EE1E95A725DC3" box="[731,826,1416,1435]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[240,289,712,731]" captionText="Fig. 23: A specimen of B. berbericola that shows an atypical enlargement of some setae and the" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
, and particularly in some specimens from the
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E1C95CE85DE3" blockId="10.[192,1440,1448,1467]" box="[192,1440,1448,1467]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
Macaronesian Islands discussed below (see 
<figureCitation id="130B8DB48E4A98230FAAE1C95AE05DE3" box="[751,936,1448,1467]" captionStart="Figures 62-80" captionStartId="14.[240,350,1224,1243]" captionText="Figures 62-80: A series of specimens in the afer group from the Canary and Madeira Islands," pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 66 and 70</figureCitation>
). (Figure reprinted by permission from
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E1A95CE85E23" blockId="10.[192,690,1480,1499]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,1640,1659]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
Springer Science+Business Media B.V.). specimen, as determined by Louise Russell, deviates little from the form of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230920E2695DFF5E43" box="[1125,1207,1544,1563]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afer">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230920E2695DFF5E43" box="[1125,1207,1544,1563]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. afer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except that it does not have the thickened crenulations at the ends of tracheal folds. Other South American specimens sometimes have microspines around the antennae and first thoracic legs and the cephalic setae are often elongated. Based on mtCO1 data, this species and 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230ED0E2095D0E5E23" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[917,1094,1640,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230ED0E2095D0E5E23" box="[917,1094,1640,1659]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, appear to be distinct from
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4A98230DB5E1895CE85DA3" box="[240,1440,1512,1531]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" startId="10.[240,289,1512,1531]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230DB5E1895CE85DA3" blockId="10.[240,1440,1512,1531]" box="[240,1440,1512,1531]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230DB5E189581F5DA3" bold="true" box="[240,343,1512,1531]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 18:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C2DE1895B9C5DA3" authority="Bondar" authorityName="Bondar" box="[360,724,1512,1531]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C2DE1895B255DA3" box="[360,621,1512,1531]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia tuberculata</emphasis>
Bondar
</taxonomicName>
is the South American member of the afer group. This
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230D85E2E95CE85F03" blockId="10.[192,1096,1672,1691]" lastBlockId="10.[192,1440,1864,1883]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
African 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C62E2E958335EC3" box="[295,379,1672,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afer">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C62E2E958335EC3" box="[295,379,1672,1691]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. afer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFA1ECC08E4A98230CCFE2E95BD65EC3" author="Gill, R. J. &amp; J. Brown" box="[394,670,1672,1691]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" pagination="1 - 29" refId="ref15774" refString="Gill, R. J., and J. Brown. 2010. Systematics of Bemisia and Bemisia relatives: can molecular techniques solve the Bemisia tabaci complex cunundrum - a taxonomist's viewpoint. p. 1 - 29. In:" type="book chapter" year="2010">Gill and Brown, 2010</bibRefCitation>
, see fig. 1.3 and 1.4, ref. TUBBZ). specimen and from 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230CF3E2A95B425E83" box="[438,522,1736,1755]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afer">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230CF3E2A95B425E83" box="[438,522,1736,1755]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. afer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having a longer lingula and pore/porette combinations that are closer together. Like 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C44E34958F05F63" box="[257,440,1832,1851]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C44E34958F05F63" box="[257,440,1832,1851]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">B. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it does not show marginal crenulation thickenings at the ends of the tracheal folds. It is most commonly found on 
<collectingRegion id="49F45FD38E4A98230FCDE3295BAD5F03" box="[648,741,1864,1883]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Oregon</collectingRegion>
grape, 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230E07E3295DD25F03" authority="Pursh." authorityName="Pursh." box="[834,1178,1864,1883]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" genus="Berberis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aquifolium">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230E07E3295D765F03" box="[834,1086,1864,1883]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Berberis aquifolium</emphasis>
Pursh.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A982309ECE3295C2A5F03" box="[1193,1378,1864,1883]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Berberidaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Ranunculales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Berberidaceae</taxonomicName>
) and
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4A98230DB5E2C95CE85EE3" box="[240,1440,1704,1723]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" startId="10.[240,289,1704,1723]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230DB5E2C95CE85EE3" blockId="10.[240,1440,1704,1723]" box="[240,1440,1704,1723]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230DB5E2C9581F5EE3" bold="true" box="[240,343,1704,1723]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 19:</emphasis>
A specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230F5CE2C95A565EE3" box="[537,798,1704,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230F5CE2C95A565EE3" box="[537,798,1704,1723]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This specimen shows variability from the above
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4A98230DB5E3695CE85F43" box="[240,1440,1800,1819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" startId="10.[240,288,1800,1819]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98230DB5E3695CE85F43" blockId="10.[240,1440,1800,1819]" box="[240,1440,1800,1819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230DB5E369581C5F43" bold="true" box="[240,340,1800,1819]" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Fig. 20:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230C1EE3695BAD5F43" authority="(Cockerell)" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[347,741,1800,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230C1EE3695B1C5F43" box="[347,596,1800,1819]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Bemisia berbericola</emphasis>
(Cockerell)
</taxonomicName>
is the North American representative of the afer group.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4A98220D85E3095CE858A3" blockId="10.[192,1441,1896,1915]" lastBlockId="11.[192,1440,232,251]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">
<collectingRegion id="49F45FD38E4A98230D85E30958085F23" box="[192,320,1896,1915]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">California</collectingRegion>
laurel, 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230CDAE3095AD75F23" authority="(Hook. and Arn.)" baseAuthorityName="Hook. and Arn." box="[415,927,1896,1915]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" genus="Umbellularia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="california">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4A98230CDAE3095B835F23" box="[415,715,1896,1915]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="9">Umbellularia california</emphasis>
(Hook. and Arn.)
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4A98230EEBE3095D7E5F23" box="[942,1078,1896,1915]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Lauraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Laurales" pageId="10" pageNumber="9" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Lauraceae</taxonomicName>
), both smooth-leafed species, and so tuberculation is usually not pronounced (but see below). The species is under excellent biocontrol in the western 
<collectingCountry id="F327D1A18E4B98220C38E48958FF58A3" box="[381,439,232,251]" name="United States of America" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">U.S.</collectingCountry>
, and is thought to be native there. However, there are similar forms in eastern
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4B98220D85E5695CE85AA3" blockId="11.[192,1440,264,283]" lastBlockId="11.[192,1440,744,763]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
Asia and 
<collectingCountry id="F327D1A18E4B98220C7DE56958C85943" box="[312,384,264,283]" name="India" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">India</collectingCountry>
. It tends to have a longer lingula than some specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220929E5695C6B5943" box="[1132,1315,264,283]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuberculata">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220929E5695C6B5943" box="[1132,1315,264,283]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. tuberculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and most specimens of African-origin afer group specimens. The lingular shape is more closely comparable with Asian specimens such as 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220F68E5295D595903" authority="(David and Subramanium)" baseAuthorityName="David and Subramanium" box="[557,1041,328,347]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moringae">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220F68E5295B8A5903" box="[557,706,328,347]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. moringae</emphasis>
(David and Subramanium)
</taxonomicName>
. (Figure reprinted by permission from Springer Science+Business Media B.V.). known which have an unusually elongated and narrow lingula. Whether this is a species level distinction or is environmentally induced is unknown. puparial characteristics. It is unusual compared to that species in that the pore/porette combinations are adjacent, although they are aligned with the porette closest to the margin, as they are in the afer groups. The specimen also has three pairs of pore/porette pairs on the first abdominal segment, and shows the development of some tuberculation on the anterior abdominal segment midlines and along the lateral edges of the dorsal disc. This specimen is from oak (
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220942E6E95DE85AC3" box="[1031,1184,648,667]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220942E6E95D385AC3" box="[1031,1136,648,667]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Quercus</emphasis>
sp.
</taxonomicName>
), which has a thick development of leaf hairs on the ventral surfaces. development of bead-like protuberances. The specimen is from Kings County, California on 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B9822087CE6895CE85AA3" box="[1337,1440,744,763]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B9822087CE6895CE85AA3" box="[1337,1440,744,763]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Quercus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4B98220DB5E5E95CE859C3" box="[240,1440,392,411]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" startId="11.[240,289,392,411]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4B98220DB5E5E95CE859C3" blockId="11.[240,1440,392,411]" box="[240,1440,392,411]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220DB5E5E9581F59C3" bold="true" box="[240,343,392,411]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Fig. 21:</emphasis>
Specimen from California near 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220FB3E5E95AE059C3" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[758,936,392,411]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220FB3E5E95AE059C3" box="[758,936,392,411]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see above). Occasional specimens are
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4B98220DB5E5895CE859A3" box="[240,1440,488,507]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" startId="11.[240,289,488,507]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4B98220DB5E5895CE859A3" blockId="11.[240,1440,488,507]" box="[240,1440,488,507]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220DB5E589581059A3" bold="true" box="[240,344,488,507]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Fig. 22:</emphasis>
This specimen, probably also 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220FA1E5895AD059A3" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[740,920,488,507]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220FA1E5895AD059A3" box="[740,920,488,507]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, shows some variation from the normal
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4B98220DB5E6A95CE85A83" box="[240,1440,712,731]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" startId="11.[240,289,712,731]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4B98220DB5E6A95CE85A83" blockId="11.[240,1440,712,731]" box="[240,1440,712,731]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220DB5E6A9581D5A83" bold="true" box="[240,341,712,731]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Fig. 23:</emphasis>
A specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220F4BE6A95BF55A83" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[526,701,712,731]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220F4BE6A95BF55A83" box="[526,701,712,731]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that shows an atypical enlargement of some setae and the
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4B98220D85E7695CE85BA3" blockId="11.[192,1440,776,795]" lastBlockId="11.[192,1440,1000,1019]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
sp., many species of which have very hirsute lower leaf surfaces in that habitat. This specimen also has adjacent pore/porette combinations like the specimen in 
<figureCitation id="130B8DB48E4B98220EF7E7495D435B63" box="[946,1035,808,827]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[240,289,488,507]" captionText="Fig. 22: This specimen, probably also B. berbericola, shows some variation from the normal" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
. The variation seen in these oak specimens are probably due to the morphology of the leaf surfaces. (Figure reprinted by permission from Springer Science+Business Media B.V.). 
<collectingRegion id="49F45FD38E4B98220D85E7C958755BE3" box="[192,317,936,955]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">California</collectingRegion>
specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220CA1E7C95BC45BE3" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[484,652,936,955]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220CA1E7C95BC45BE3" box="[484,652,936,955]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is one of 
<specimenCount id="9D365AB88E4B98220E64E7C95AAF5BE3" box="[801,999,936,955]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" type="generic">three specimens</specimenCount>
collected from two widely separated locations on 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220C25E7A95A1A5B83" authority="Hook &amp; Arn." authorityName="Hook &amp; Arn." box="[352,850,968,987]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Adenostoma" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fasciculatum">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220C25E7A95BE35B83" box="[352,683,968,987]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Adenostoma fasciculatum</emphasis>
Hook &amp; Arn.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220E27E7A95A965B83" box="[866,990,968,987]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
). The leaflets of this plant are tiny and cylindrical, 
<quantity id="4CC83CD48E4B98220CCBE78958B45BA3" box="[398,508,1000,1019]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="7.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="4.0">4-10 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity id="4CC83CD48E4B98220F33E7895BF45BA3" box="[630,700,1000,1019]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
wide. The puparium is elongate in shape instead of ovoid/
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF4FC1B98E4B98220DB5E7E95CE85BC3" box="[240,1440,904,923]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" startId="11.[240,289,904,923]">
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4B98220DB5E7E95CE85BC3" blockId="11.[240,1440,904,923]" box="[240,1440,904,923]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220DB5E7E9581D5BC3" bold="true" box="[240,341,904,923]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">Fig. 24:</emphasis>
An atypical specimen referable to 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220E4EE7E95AF35BC3" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[779,955,904,923]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220E4EE7E95AF35BC3" box="[779,955,904,923]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This specimen is different from other
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B8F91318E4B98220D85E0695D525CC3" blockId="11.[192,1440,1032,1051]" lastBlockId="11.[192,1050,1160,1179]" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">
circular as in 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220C2AE0695B575C43" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[367,543,1032,1051]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220C2AE0695B575C43" box="[367,543,1032,1051]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, has an extremely long lingula, and the pore/porette combinations are sparse in the area between the submargin and the outer edges of the dorsal disc. There is a continuous row of pore/porettes along the submargin, and there are a few raised tuberculations. The variations here are apparently associated with the host leaf morphology. Whether this is a separate species from 
<taxonomicName id="4C30EAB28E4B98220C46E0E958FB5CC3" baseAuthorityName="Cockerell" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[259,435,1160,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Aleyrodidae" genus="Bemisia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="berbericola">
<emphasis id="B9444D238E4B98220C46E0E958FB5CC3" box="[259,435,1160,1179]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="10">B. berbericola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or adaptation to the leaf structure is not known.
</paragraph>
